09:13.888 --> 09:16.630
Come on, guys.
You're gonna be late for school.

09:17.630 --> 09:20.483
Kev. Baseball cards
back up in your room, please.

09:20.568 --> 09:22.702
Hustle, Kevin. I'm meeting
Mrs. Hollins before class

09:22.787 --> 09:24.077
to talk about
changing my grade.

09:24.162 --> 09:26.365
Can you take me to the baseball
card store after school?

09:26.450 --> 09:27.686
Nope. I'm sorry,
I don't have time.

09:27.770 --> 09:29.928
I have errands to run:
grocery store, bank,

09:30.013 --> 09:32.663
library, dry cleaning.
Sorry.

09:32.747 --> 09:34.498
Then, can you give me the money
for my two As?

09:34.582 --> 09:36.333
I want to feel it burning
in my pocket all day.

09:36.417 --> 09:38.538
Hey, Kev, come on,
baseball cards upstairs.

09:38.623 --> 09:40.406
Randall, you remember
I'm picking you up from school?

09:40.490 --> 09:41.505
‐ You got your stuff?
‐ Yeah.

09:41.589 --> 09:42.673
Okay, good. Wait in the car.

09:42.757 --> 09:44.466
Hey, Kate? Come on!

09:44.550 --> 09:46.844
♪ I'll be loving you ♪

09:46.928 --> 09:49.805
♪ Forever... ♪

09:49.889 --> 09:51.348
Bug?

09:51.432 --> 09:52.683
It's time to go.

09:52.767 --> 09:54.934
I go. I stay.

09:55.019 --> 09:56.604
What does it matter?

09:57.451 --> 09:59.869
I'm gonna go to the market
a little later today.

09:59.962 --> 10:02.256
Do you have any requests
for dinner?

10:02.628 --> 10:04.337
Three‐ cheese macaroni?

10:04.422 --> 10:06.138
You got it.

10:07.002 --> 10:09.428
‐ Hi.
‐ How about after school

10:09.513 --> 10:10.951
I come with you
on your errands,

10:11.035 --> 10:12.703
and then we can swing by
the card store afterwards?

10:12.787 --> 10:14.325
Fine.

10:14.455 --> 10:16.164
Okay, let's go.

10:16.248 --> 10:17.708
("Both Sides, Now"
by Joni Mitchell playing)

10:17.792 --> 10:21.879
♪ Rows and flows of angel hair ♪

10:21.963 --> 10:26.842
♪ And ice cream castles
in the air ♪

10:26.926 --> 10:29.803
♪ And feather canyons ♪

10:29.887 --> 10:33.056
♪ Everywhere ♪

10:33.140 --> 10:37.561
♪ I've looked at clouds
that way, but now... ♪

10:37.645 --> 10:39.229
‐ (chuckles)
‐ (music stops)

10:39.313 --> 10:42.858
Ah.

10:42.942 --> 10:45.027
I miss that crackle

10:45.111 --> 10:47.905
on the record before the music.

10:47.989 --> 10:49.907
Joni...

10:49.991 --> 10:51.241
I would spend

10:51.325 --> 10:54.829
hours staring
at this album artwork.

10:55.830 --> 10:58.415
Reading all the sleeve notes.

10:58.499 --> 11:00.042
Okay, boomer.

11:00.126 --> 11:02.920
Ha, you can laugh at me
all you want,

11:03.004 --> 11:05.213
but my record collection...

11:05.297 --> 11:08.259
was my whole world.

11:09.677 --> 11:11.929
Kind of like you
and your baseball cards.

11:12.013 --> 11:14.222
‐ (laughs): Oh, okay.
‐ Mm‐ hmm.

11:14.306 --> 11:16.224
All right, no,
my‐ my baseball cards, that,

11:16.308 --> 11:18.060
that was, that was real,

11:18.144 --> 11:19.825
that was a collection, okay?

11:19.910 --> 11:22.068
There‐ there was strategy
involved, there was commerce.

11:22.152 --> 11:23.831
‐ I mean, the whole thing.
‐ Oh, I remember.

11:23.915 --> 11:25.786
‐ Yeah.
‐ Mm‐ hmm.

11:29.822 --> 11:31.698
(laughs)

11:31.782 --> 11:33.951
Did I ever tell you
the first time

11:34.035 --> 11:35.577
your father and I
came out to I. A.,

11:35.661 --> 11:37.621
we tried to find
Joni Mitchell's old house

11:37.705 --> 11:40.124
in, um, Laurel Canyon?

11:42.043 --> 11:45.128
I think we passed Mount Olympus.

11:45.376 --> 11:47.879
You sure the map's
not upside‐ down?

11:48.883 --> 11:51.134
(laughs) No.

11:51.218 --> 11:53.720
We got close, we even

11:53.804 --> 11:55.481
wandered around
Joni's neighborhood,

11:55.566 --> 11:58.083
but we never found the house,

11:58.168 --> 12:00.796
so... we gave up.

12:02.566 --> 12:04.400
Maybe we should
finish the job, you know?

12:04.648 --> 12:06.984
We'll find Joni Mitchell's
old house.

12:07.068 --> 12:08.151
How?

12:08.235 --> 12:09.611
‐ Hey, Siri?
‐ (phone chimes)

12:09.695 --> 12:11.571
Where's Joni Mitchell's
old house?

12:11.655 --> 12:13.657
‐ What are you doing?
‐ SIRI: Here's what I found on the Web.

12:13.741 --> 12:15.325
‐ Is that it? That her house?
‐ (gasps)

12:15.409 --> 12:17.481
‐ Oh, my goodness, yes!
‐ Yeah?

12:17.566 --> 12:19.579
Yes, that‐ that's the house.

12:19.663 --> 12:20.998
Well, uh, do you think
we have time, though,

12:21.082 --> 12:22.295
before your doctor's
appointment?

12:22.379 --> 12:24.583
Well, if we don't have time,
we're gonna make time.

12:24.668 --> 12:26.841
‐ Okay, Carpe Diem Rebecca.
‐ Yes.

12:26.926 --> 12:28.216
Here we go, all right.

12:32.051 --> 12:33.343
Hey, girl.

12:33.427 --> 12:34.929
Get over here.

12:36.097 --> 12:37.755
It's nice to see you.

12:41.052 --> 12:42.811
Isn't this place cute?

12:42.895 --> 12:44.787
I love coming here for brunch.

12:44.872 --> 12:46.773
It's hip but still normal...

12:46.857 --> 12:48.389
Okay, Madison, let's
just cut the preamble.

12:48.473 --> 12:50.818
Okay, let's just
get it over with.

12:50.903 --> 12:52.536
I screwed up.

12:52.754 --> 12:54.169
You are so important to me,

12:54.254 --> 12:56.005
and friends don't
do that to friends.

12:56.090 --> 12:57.442
Or their brothers.

12:57.527 --> 12:59.487
Honestly, I don't know
what I was thinking.

12:59.572 --> 13:01.327
Other than I have never
seen anyone so hot

13:01.412 --> 13:02.856
and so vulnerable
at the same time.

13:02.941 --> 13:04.184
My brain just shorted.

13:04.269 --> 13:05.688
I mean, I know he's
your brother, but...

13:05.772 --> 13:07.064
my God.

13:07.542 --> 13:08.817
I am so sorry.

13:08.902 --> 13:10.820
I am ashamed and embarrassed,

13:10.999 --> 13:13.084
and it'll never happen again.

13:15.302 --> 13:17.888
I really don't know what
to think about all of this.

13:17.972 --> 13:21.058
And it really couldn't have come
at a more terrible time.

13:21.142 --> 13:23.185
Is it that CrossFit bitch?

13:23.269 --> 13:24.352
I'll kill her.

13:24.436 --> 13:25.395
Is it Toby?

13:25.479 --> 13:26.563
I'll kill him.

13:26.647 --> 13:27.898
You just say the word,

13:27.982 --> 13:29.149
I will Kill Bill all of them

13:29.233 --> 13:31.902
and help you raise
that child myself.

13:31.986 --> 13:34.029
Talk to me, Kate.

13:34.113 --> 13:35.781
Please?

13:41.829 --> 13:44.247
So, how we doing this, Doc...
is it Good Will Hunting

13:44.331 --> 13:45.661
or The Sopranos?

13:45.746 --> 13:47.456
No, I'm just playing. I, um...

13:47.835 --> 13:50.879
I'm comfortable
speaking about my emotions.

13:50.963 --> 13:52.395
I'm an emotional man.

13:52.574 --> 13:53.950
No shame.

13:54.035 --> 13:55.077
Uh... (clears throat)

13:55.162 --> 13:57.075
before we start, let me just...

13:57.629 --> 14:00.036
...put this on silent.

14:01.661 --> 14:03.537
(exhales)

14:04.520 --> 14:07.187
My, uh, mom's got a doctor's
appointment today,

14:07.271 --> 14:10.607
but there's no need
for any distractions, right?

14:10.691 --> 14:12.025
Okay.

14:12.109 --> 14:13.735
All yours.

14:13.819 --> 14:15.278
Is she okay?

14:15.362 --> 14:17.113
Ah, she's fine.

14:17.197 --> 14:19.950
Um, early signs of dementia,

14:20.034 --> 14:21.284
but we're on top of it.

14:21.368 --> 14:22.701
Today's just
a follow‐ up appointment,

14:22.785 --> 14:26.705
but that's‐ that's
not why I'm here.

14:27.041 --> 14:29.376
So, why are you here?

14:32.200 --> 14:33.617
Um...

14:34.287 --> 14:36.831
I have anxiety.

14:37.009 --> 14:38.969
Suffer from, is that the...?

14:39.053 --> 14:41.013
Doesn't matter.

14:42.348 --> 14:45.528
Maybe once every decade
things get too...

14:45.613 --> 14:47.447
overwhelming.

14:47.939 --> 14:49.559
I'll have a panic attack.

14:49.644 --> 14:51.061
I'll be hospitalized.

14:51.146 --> 14:53.898
That's happened twice.

14:54.450 --> 14:57.320
My house was
recently broken into.

14:57.825 --> 15:01.492
My wife's worried about
history repeating itself.

15:03.327 --> 15:05.829
So, my‐ my daughter Tess...

15:05.913 --> 15:08.790
uh... I have three daughters.

15:08.874 --> 15:12.502
Anyway, Tess sees a therapist.

15:12.586 --> 15:15.255
(nearby hissing)

15:16.364 --> 15:18.466
Um... (clears throat)
it's really helped her.

15:18.997 --> 15:20.844
So, I think that's

15:20.928 --> 15:22.304
what I'm looking
to get out of this is

15:22.388 --> 15:24.395
coping mechanisms.

15:25.265 --> 15:27.475
Okay, well,
before we get to that,

15:27.559 --> 15:30.520
I'd like to know
a little more about you.

15:30.604 --> 15:32.314
I'm an open book...
where do you want to start?

15:32.398 --> 15:33.773
The beginning?

15:34.067 --> 15:35.739
So, I'm actually adopted.

15:35.824 --> 15:38.443
I was left at a fire station
the day I was born,

15:38.528 --> 15:39.988
and a fireman took me
to the hospital,

15:40.072 --> 15:42.236
- where he met my parents...
- I'm so sorry.

15:42.681 --> 15:46.327
(groans) Before we get
too far into the weeds here,

15:46.412 --> 15:49.372
full disclosure...
I do know who you are.

15:49.689 --> 15:53.673
I've actually heard that story
in one of your speeches.

15:54.111 --> 15:56.964
In many of your speeches,
actually.

16:01.435 --> 16:03.345
Oh, you know...

16:06.244 --> 16:07.828
...my speeches.

16:08.100 --> 16:10.519
(nearby hissing)

16:15.338 --> 16:16.893
‐ Mom?
‐ Yes, Kevin?

16:16.978 --> 16:19.105
‐ Baseball cards.
‐ (chuckles) Not yet.

16:19.190 --> 16:20.721
(groans) So unfair.

16:20.806 --> 16:24.142
Well, so is life.

16:24.445 --> 16:26.863
Look, you‐ you're making
Kate's favorite dinner

16:26.947 --> 16:28.111
because she got dumped.

16:28.196 --> 16:30.596
And you're returning
Randall's library books

16:30.681 --> 16:31.952
because he's a massive nerd.

16:32.036 --> 16:33.537
The least you could do
is give me

16:33.621 --> 16:35.322
five minutes
at the baseball card store.

16:35.407 --> 16:38.206
Uh, I didn't go to the grocery
store just for Kate.

16:38.291 --> 16:40.745
I also bought groceries,
including two chickens

16:40.830 --> 16:42.837
that I will cook
for the whole family.

16:42.978 --> 16:44.807
I wish you were more
like Sophie's mom.

16:44.892 --> 16:46.340
She's fun.

16:47.235 --> 16:48.860
Uh... I'm fun.

16:49.517 --> 16:51.720
I am as fun as Sophie's mom.

16:51.805 --> 16:53.222
I am a fun mom.

16:53.307 --> 16:55.572
(laughs)

16:55.976 --> 16:59.021
Oh, wait, are you being serious?

16:59.886 --> 17:01.304
Okay, fine.

17:01.482 --> 17:03.984
Fine. We will go
to the baseball card store.

17:04.068 --> 17:05.569
‐ Yes.
‐ Because I'm fun.

17:05.653 --> 17:07.237
‐ But five minutes only.
‐ Okay.

17:07.320 --> 17:08.696
Five minutes, Kevin,
you hear me?

17:08.781 --> 17:10.160
‐ Got it.
‐ Seriously. We have groceries,

17:10.243 --> 17:11.276
including frozen vegetables

17:11.359 --> 17:13.278
‐ and dairy.
‐ All right. Thank you.

17:13.452 --> 17:15.246
[♪ ♪]

17:19.791 --> 17:21.710
I cannot believe I'm here.

17:21.794 --> 17:23.252
‐ Yeah.
‐ Kevin.

17:23.337 --> 17:25.422
You know, Joni Mitchell lived
in this house

17:25.506 --> 17:27.424
‐ with Graham Nash.
‐ Wow.

17:30.590 --> 17:32.425
Wait, what are you doing?

17:32.665 --> 17:34.166
I was gonna ring the bell.

17:34.383 --> 17:36.218
Don't you want to see inside?

17:36.531 --> 17:38.991
Isn't that rude
to just show up unannounced?

17:39.090 --> 17:41.553
It's not fair, but being
a celebrity is like having

17:41.638 --> 17:42.940
a Fast Pass
to pretty much everything

17:43.024 --> 17:44.943
‐ you want to do in life.
‐ (line ringing)

17:49.344 --> 17:50.679
Hmm.

17:50.865 --> 17:53.330
Except of course
making people magically home.

17:54.337 --> 17:55.526
‐ Oh.
‐ Mom?

17:55.611 --> 17:56.620
It's open.

17:56.704 --> 17:58.038
(whispers):
It's open. Come on.

17:58.122 --> 17:59.289
‐ Mom.
‐ (laughs): Come on.

17:59.373 --> 18:01.838
All right.
If I end up on TMZ

18:01.923 --> 18:03.460
for breaking
into Joni Mitchell's old house

18:03.544 --> 18:05.267
with my mom...

18:06.470 --> 18:08.845
Actually, I mean,
that could play.

18:10.075 --> 18:12.327
Hey, Dad?
I have an "A" in P.E.

18:12.473 --> 18:14.391
I really don't need
to be doing this.

18:14.530 --> 18:16.448
It's not about grades, Randall.

18:16.650 --> 18:20.206
Exercise is about
getting blood moving

18:20.291 --> 18:22.237
through your whole body.

18:22.322 --> 18:25.518
Okay? Now, I want you to run
until that worried feeling

18:25.603 --> 18:27.337
in the pit of your stomach
goes away.

18:28.541 --> 18:30.095
I really don't like running.

18:30.180 --> 18:32.103
Yeah. How about racing?

18:32.236 --> 18:33.947
Huh? Come on.

18:34.032 --> 18:36.826
You and me,
once around the track.

18:37.041 --> 18:39.459
I'll even give you a head start.

18:39.544 --> 18:41.755
(Jack groans loudly)

18:42.739 --> 18:44.032
Yeah.

18:44.947 --> 18:46.698
Hey, just do me a favor?

18:47.111 --> 18:49.447
Try and make it interesting.

18:50.986 --> 18:53.220
Okay, runners.

18:53.661 --> 18:56.121
On your marks...

18:56.206 --> 18:58.025
get set...

18:58.124 --> 18:59.650
‐ Go!
‐ RANDALL: I guess

18:59.735 --> 19:02.140
what I'm saying is, I'm
fortunate to have been shaped

19:02.225 --> 19:03.726
by two incredible fathers...

19:04.099 --> 19:07.060
the one I lost
and the one I gained.

19:08.619 --> 19:10.454
It's in my speeches

19:10.539 --> 19:11.775
for a reason.

19:11.860 --> 19:14.494
‐ Of course.
‐ Yeah, of course.

19:14.977 --> 19:17.339
You know, I can't help but feel

19:17.424 --> 19:19.431
like I'm throwing
off my back foot here.

19:19.516 --> 19:22.477
It's like you googled me.
Isn't that against the rules?

19:23.759 --> 19:24.954
I mean, I just find it weird

19:25.039 --> 19:26.502
that you waited
to bring that up.

19:26.587 --> 19:28.255
You knew...

19:30.388 --> 19:31.764
No, I'm sorry.

19:32.004 --> 19:33.143
(takes deep breath)
I'm sorry.

19:33.227 --> 19:36.563
I'm only gonna get out of it
what I put in, right?

19:37.218 --> 19:39.228
Not your fault.

19:39.509 --> 19:42.548
I'm a public figure...
I shouldn't have been surprised.

19:44.156 --> 19:46.199
Where were we?

19:46.885 --> 19:48.377
Family.

19:48.688 --> 19:51.649
(sighs):
Family. Sure. Of course.

19:51.905 --> 19:53.865
(nearby hissing)

19:56.261 --> 19:58.705
I just told him
it‐ it wasn't enough

19:59.073 --> 20:00.783
for him to want to be

20:00.875 --> 20:02.017
a good father.

20:02.102 --> 20:03.712
Just needs to be one.

20:04.412 --> 20:06.163
And now I don't even know
if he's being sincere

20:06.247 --> 20:07.932
or if he's just telling me
what I want to hear.

20:08.016 --> 20:09.934
Could it be both?

20:10.019 --> 20:13.677
I mean... trust me,
I will take whatever position

20:13.762 --> 20:15.180
you take right now.

20:15.389 --> 20:17.877
But is it possible he just took
what you said to heart?

20:19.424 --> 20:21.050
I don't know.

20:22.275 --> 20:24.580
Do you want to know
why I think I slept with Kevin?

20:24.665 --> 20:26.939
‐ Um, no. Mm‐ mm.
‐ It was nice to be

20:27.024 --> 20:29.369
with someone who actually knew
something about me.

20:29.533 --> 20:33.119
As opposed to...
Tinder dates or being set up.

20:33.477 --> 20:36.400
I mean, he has seen me
at the hospital with no makeup.

20:36.485 --> 20:40.238
And at your house not trying
to be perky or appealing.

20:40.713 --> 20:44.596
What you and Toby have,
what I dream of finding,

20:44.681 --> 20:46.349
is that intimacy.

20:47.002 --> 20:49.611
It's letting people see
the worst part of you without...

20:49.696 --> 20:51.615
being scared.

20:52.372 --> 20:56.033
And I am just
gonna say this and duck.

20:56.613 --> 20:59.722
But shouldn't Toby be able
to express his deepest fears

20:59.807 --> 21:01.127
without punishment?

21:01.469 --> 21:03.720
Isn't that what marriage is?

21:03.804 --> 21:04.979
Okay.

21:05.064 --> 21:07.393
When did you become
the counselor of relationships

21:07.478 --> 21:08.986
with Bachelor in Paradise?

21:09.135 --> 21:12.291
I listen to a lot
of relationship podcasts.

21:12.376 --> 21:14.461
I keep hoping
I'll need them someday.

21:14.748 --> 21:16.111
(Kate chuckles)

21:16.196 --> 21:17.823
So, are we good?

21:18.103 --> 21:20.021
(sighs)
Yes.

21:20.106 --> 21:21.773
But you're on probation.

21:21.858 --> 21:23.359
You love me.

21:23.723 --> 21:25.416
Most of the time.

21:25.501 --> 21:27.545
Can I just tell you one thing
your brother did to me?

21:27.629 --> 21:29.756
‐ No. ‐ I was literally
upside‐ down at one point.

21:29.841 --> 21:32.635
‐ Madison.
‐ Just use your imagination.

21:35.760 --> 21:38.918
Hey. You got
any '91s left, Carl?

21:39.003 --> 21:42.047
Ooh, not many.
What are you looking for, Kev?

21:42.131 --> 21:46.551
I need a '91 John Candelaria
to finish off last year's set.

21:46.635 --> 21:48.010
I got ten bucks to do it.

21:48.157 --> 21:51.889
Well, I've got
only 16 packs left,

21:51.974 --> 21:53.307
but I like your chances

21:53.392 --> 21:55.893
‐ of finding it. ‐ Great,
I'll take 'em. Thank you.

21:55.978 --> 21:57.896
Eight dollars and 40 cents.

21:59.072 --> 22:00.614
(Rebecca laughs)

22:00.791 --> 22:03.586
Right.

22:05.112 --> 22:07.156
(Rebecca sighs)

22:14.401 --> 22:16.403
No John Candlemalaria?

22:16.707 --> 22:18.393
No?

22:18.478 --> 22:20.104
(Rebecca sighs)

22:21.096 --> 22:22.963
Well, buck up, sweetheart.

22:23.047 --> 22:25.736
You have, what, 14 packs left?

22:28.719 --> 22:30.846
Here. Blow on this one...
for good luck.

22:30.931 --> 22:33.475
(laughs, blows)

22:36.894 --> 22:39.312
Oh, gosh, this gum is really
not very good.

22:39.396 --> 22:40.815
The flavor only lasts a minute.

22:40.900 --> 22:43.471
You got to replace it,
like, every 60 seconds.

22:47.404 --> 22:48.924
‐ I feel good about this one.
‐ Yeah?

22:49.009 --> 22:51.261
Yeah, yeah. Come on.

22:51.346 --> 22:52.763
‐ Cool.
‐ Hey!

22:52.848 --> 22:54.558
Batter, batter, batter, swing!

22:54.643 --> 22:56.353
Come on.
(rubbing hands together)

22:57.597 --> 23:00.933
Did you know that Graham Nash
wrote the song "Our House"

23:01.392 --> 23:02.976
about this house?

23:03.061 --> 23:04.002
‐ Oh, really?
‐ Mm‐ hmm.

23:04.087 --> 23:05.744
‐ Huh.
‐ One morning

23:05.829 --> 23:08.174
Joni and Graham went down
to the Valley

23:08.259 --> 23:10.011
to have breakfast at Art's Deli.

23:10.096 --> 23:13.894
And after breakfast they were
walking down Ventura Boulevard,

23:13.979 --> 23:15.705
and Joni spotted this vase

23:15.790 --> 23:17.833
in a store window
that she really liked.

23:17.918 --> 23:19.378
Mm‐ hmm.

23:19.648 --> 23:21.357
So they bought it.

23:21.441 --> 23:24.527
And they brought it back home,
and Graham suggested

23:24.611 --> 23:27.989
that Joni pick some flowers
for the vase

23:28.073 --> 23:30.072
while he built a fire.

23:30.432 --> 23:31.827
Mm‐ hmm.

23:34.822 --> 23:37.157
♪ I'll light the fire ♪

23:37.444 --> 23:39.779
♪ You place the flowers ♪

23:39.864 --> 23:45.190
♪ In the vase
that you bought today ♪

23:45.343 --> 23:47.595
♪ Staring at the fire ♪

23:47.820 --> 23:50.071
♪ For hours and hours... ♪

23:50.178 --> 23:51.846
‐ Come on, Jack.
‐ No, no, I...

23:51.930 --> 23:53.931
♪ While I listen to you ♪

23:54.015 --> 23:56.604
♪ Play your love songs ♪

23:56.810 --> 24:00.605
♪ All night long for me ♪

24:00.876 --> 24:05.077
♪ Only for me‐ ee‐ ee ♪

24:05.971 --> 24:09.471
♪ Come to me now ♪

24:09.556 --> 24:13.330
♪ Rest your head
for just five minutes ♪

24:13.440 --> 24:16.260
♪ Everything ♪

24:16.345 --> 24:18.430
♪ Is done. ♪

24:20.876 --> 24:23.586
‐ You still got it.
‐ Hmm.

24:24.315 --> 24:27.089
An otherwise simple morning
might have been forgotten

24:27.236 --> 24:29.614
if it weren't for that song.

24:37.844 --> 24:39.533
Are you scared?

24:43.736 --> 24:45.483
A little.

24:45.885 --> 24:48.069
But I'm not even thinking
about any of that right now

24:48.153 --> 24:51.572
'cause I am...
I'm right here with you.

24:53.124 --> 24:56.057
You've always had
that quality, Kevin.

24:57.435 --> 24:59.353
You make everything fun.

24:59.484 --> 25:02.534
Which I know you probably think
is a bad thing sometimes,

25:02.619 --> 25:03.835
and maybe people don't
take you seriously.

25:03.919 --> 25:05.502
You're ice cold.
Let me try. Let me try.

25:05.587 --> 25:07.004
Ready?
(exhales sharply)

25:07.443 --> 25:09.487
Okay. Okay.

25:12.552 --> 25:14.220
Nope.

25:16.116 --> 25:18.243
It's not it.

25:19.184 --> 25:20.854
What?

25:23.188 --> 25:26.858
Sometimes making people forget
about their worries,

25:26.942 --> 25:30.190
or what comes next...

25:30.619 --> 25:35.111
that's the most important thing
you can do for someone.

25:38.351 --> 25:41.204
LEIGH: So,
we've talked about your panic attacks

25:41.289 --> 25:44.876
and your relationship
with your two fathers.

25:44.960 --> 25:47.795
How is your relationship
with your mother?

25:47.879 --> 25:49.213
It's good.

25:49.297 --> 25:50.986
I love my mother.

25:52.574 --> 25:54.575
We're very close.
(laughs)

25:54.886 --> 25:57.167
If you sense me tensing up
right now,

25:57.252 --> 25:58.222
it's because of her illness,

25:58.306 --> 26:00.558
not because
of my relationship with her.

26:00.799 --> 26:03.185
Trust me when I say
I'm not here because of her.

26:03.269 --> 26:05.361
I'm here
because I have control issues.

26:05.569 --> 26:08.404
Is that your... self‐ diagnosis?

26:08.566 --> 26:10.799
I think it's kind of obvious.

26:12.303 --> 26:15.162
Like how you're trying
to control the conversation away

26:15.247 --> 26:17.666
from talking about your mom?

26:21.240 --> 26:23.284
Okay, Dr. Melfi.

26:24.129 --> 26:25.705
I get it.

26:26.167 --> 26:28.085
I get what you're doing here.

26:28.169 --> 26:29.424
(nearby hissing)

26:29.509 --> 26:32.463
I mean, is it broke
or something? What's the...?

26:32.688 --> 26:35.815
Do you want to talk about why
that's bothering you?

26:35.900 --> 26:38.652
(sighs heavily)

26:39.179 --> 26:42.572
But then I would have to admit
that it's bothering me.

26:43.122 --> 26:45.182
Ha, ha.

26:45.289 --> 26:48.333
Okay. All right.

26:48.418 --> 26:52.463
So... this is all part of it,
right?

26:52.944 --> 26:55.221
The waiting room, the painting?

26:55.321 --> 26:56.971
Is that how
your operation works?

26:57.056 --> 27:00.486
Just agitate your patients
into having a breakdown?

27:00.571 --> 27:03.322
‐ (phone buzzing)
‐ Ah, apologies.

27:03.407 --> 27:05.826
I need to check this.

27:09.711 --> 27:11.796
(smacks lips)
Oh, good.

27:11.943 --> 27:14.455
Looks like my brother
will be taking my mom

27:14.540 --> 27:16.932
to her follow‐ up appointment
today.

27:17.221 --> 27:18.635
What could go wrong?

27:18.720 --> 27:20.513
(nearby hissing)

27:21.612 --> 27:25.222
♪ All I can say is that
my life is pretty plain ♪

27:25.307 --> 27:26.933
(door opens)

27:27.017 --> 27:29.097
♪ I like watchin' ♪

27:29.182 --> 27:31.916
♪ The puddles gather rain... ♪

27:32.019 --> 27:35.439
‐ (door closes) ‐ Hey, bud,
take your stuff upstairs, okay?

27:35.656 --> 27:37.657
Thanks. (sighs)

27:37.742 --> 27:39.260
Hi.

27:39.345 --> 27:42.307
♪ And speak
my point of view... ♪

27:42.392 --> 27:45.518
Look, I‐ I know you don't want
to talk about Stuart, all right?

27:45.603 --> 27:48.787
‐ Especially not with your dad.
‐ I don't.

27:48.872 --> 27:50.915
(Jack sighs)

27:50.999 --> 27:53.057
♪ I just want someone
to say... ♪

27:53.142 --> 27:56.729
Hey, do you know how,
some Saturdays,

27:57.721 --> 28:00.883
when I make waffles, you guys
see me toss the first one out?

28:01.385 --> 28:03.803
That's because
the waffle iron is too hot,

28:03.887 --> 28:05.805
or maybe
it's not hot enough, or,

28:05.889 --> 28:08.474
you know,
I made the batter too thick.

28:08.799 --> 28:12.895
First boyfriends are kind of
like first waffles.

28:13.986 --> 28:15.565
Okay? You‐ you got to...

28:16.119 --> 28:18.818
get through a few
before you get it right.

28:18.902 --> 28:21.698
♪ I sleep all day... ♪

